Here is a simple example of how to use JNI (Java Native Interface) in C++:

Java code:

```java
public class MyClass {
   private native void myFunction();

   static {
      System.loadLibrary("mylib");
   }

   public static void main(String[] args) {
      new MyClass().myFunction();
   }
}
```

C++ code:

```c++
#include 

JNIEXPORT void JNICALL Java_MyClass_myFunction(JNIEnv *, jobject) {
   // do something
}

JNIEXPORT jint JNICALL JNI_OnLoad(JavaVM *vm, void *reserved) {
   JNIEnv *env;
   if (vm->GetEnv(reinterpret_cast(&env), JNI_VERSION_1_6) != JNI_OK) {
      return JNI_ERR;
   }

   jclass cls = env->FindClass("MyClass");
   if (cls == nullptr) {
      return JNI_ERR;
   }

   static const JNINativeMethod methods[] = {
      { "myFunction", "()V", reinterpret_cast(Java_MyClass_myFunction) }
   };

   jint res = env->RegisterNatives(cls, methods, sizeof(methods) / sizeof(JNINativeMethod));
   if (res < 0) {
      return JNI_ERR;
   }

   return JNI_VERSION_1_6;
}
```

This code defines a native function `myFunction` in C++ that the `MyClass` Java class loads and calls. `JNI_OnLoad` is a special function that gets called when the library is loaded by the JVM, and it registers the native functions that can be called from Java.

how can we implement object pooling in u:
Object pooling can be implemented in Unity by following these steps:

1. Create a new script and name it "ObjectPool".
2. In the script, create a list of GameObjects.
3. In the Start function, populate the list with instantiated game objects.
4. Add a function to get an object from the pool by checking for any inactive objects in the list.
5. Add a function to return an object to the pool by disabling it and adding it back to the list.
6. Update your game code to use the object pool instead of constantly instantiating and destroying game objects.
7. Finally, use the profiler to measure the performance gain.

Example code:

```
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class ObjectPool : MonoBehaviour
{
    [SerializeField] private GameObject objectToPool;
    [SerializeField] private int initialPoolSize;
    private List pool;

    private void Start()
    {
        pool = new List();
        for (int i = 0; i < initialPoolSize; i++)
        {
            GameObject obj = Instantiate(objectToPool);
            obj.SetActive(false);
            pool.Add(obj);
        }
    }

    public GameObject GetObject()
    {
        foreach (GameObject obj in pool)
        {
            if (!obj.activeInHierarchy)
            {
                obj.SetActive(true);
                return obj;
            }
        }

        GameObject newObj = Instantiate(objectToPool);
        pool.Add(newObj);
        return newObj;
    }

    public void ReturnObject(GameObject obj)
    {
        obj.SetActive(false);
    }
}
```

To use the object pool, simply call `GetObject()` when you need a new object and `ReturnObject()` when you are done with it. This will improve performance by reducing the number of times Unity has to destroy and instantiate game objects.

